Goal:
Extend the existing Apple Music playlist management code to automatically
classify playlists into folders based on the songs inside.

Target genre folders:
- hiphop
- electronic
- disco_funk_soul
- jazz
- world
- rock

Requirements:
- Integrate with your existing AppleScript code for reading playlists and tracks
- Extract metadata for each track: genre, artist, bpm, year, composer
- Normalize all text fields (lowercase, trim)
- Map raw genres to predefined clusters (e.g., "trap" → "hiphop")
- Score playlists using weighted rules:
    - genre match: +3
    - artist match (lookup lists per genre): +2
    - composer match (especially jazz/world): +1
    - bpm range match (for electronic/disco): +1
- Determine dominant genre per playlist using weighted scores
- Apply ML-based fallback (TF-IDF on genre strings) only if scoring is ambiguous
- Create playlist folders in Apple Music if missing
- Move playlists into the dominant genre folder
- Preserve playlists that don’t meet dominance threshold (skip or mark as "unsorted")

Implementation notes:
- Keep AppleScript strictly for I/O: reading tracks and moving playlists
- Perform scoring, artist-lookup, TF-IDF, and dominance calculation in JS/Python
- Dry-run mode: optional flag that logs all intended moves without modifying Apple Music
- Include verbose logging for each playlist:
    - Track-level scores
    - Playlist-level scores
    - Dominant genre decision
    - Skip reasons
- Allow configuration via local files:
    - genre_map.json
    - weights.json
    - artists/*.txt for artist lookup lists
- Make the system modular so existing code can be reused without rewriting
- Integrate cached web sources for additional artist/genre data
  (Discogs, MusicBrainz, Last.fm, RateYourMusic)